<div class="col-12 col-lg-7">
  <div class="card h-100 shadow-sm">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h2 class="h4">Endecott yDNA Project Goals</h2>

      <!-- 1–2 with sub-points -->
      <ol class="mb-3">
        <li>
          Identify the father of Governor John Endecott (1588–1665)
          <ul class="mt-2">
            <li>Is it Thomas Endecott (1566–1621) of Chagford, England?</li>
            <li>Maybe one of Thomas Endecott’s (b. 1566) siblings?</li>
            <li>Maybe a distant relative of Thomas Endecott (b. 1566)?</li>
            <li>Could it be a man with an unknown surname?</li>
            <li>Could Gov. John Endecott be a descendant of the Yorkshire Endeacotts (“ae” spelling)?</li>
            <li>Some have claimed Gov. John’s parents were from Dorchester, England—another possibility?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>
          Identify the family lines of various Endecott families from around the world
          <ul class="mt-2">
            <li>Variant spellings: Endecott, Endicott, Endacott, Indicott, Endeacott, …</li>
            <li>Large groups in the USA, England, South Africa, Australia, New Zealand, …</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- Continue numbering at 5 exactly as provided -->
      <ol start="5" class="mb-0">
        <li>Rule out whether certain families only took on the Endecott surname when surnames were required</li>
        <li>Compare all Endecott family lines and determine where they fit into the haplogroup tree</li>
        <li>Determine places of origin associated with submitted DNA samples</li>
        <li>Determine the specific branch the tester belongs to</li>
        <li>Determine if other surnames are associated with the Endecott surname</li>
        <li>Determine if the tester is genetically related to others who share the Endecott (and variations) surname</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
        <strong>New to yDNA?</strong> Only males can take a Y-DNA test; it traces the direct paternal line and places you in a haplogroup. Big&nbsp;Y-700 gives the best resolution for this project.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

