<div class="col-12">
  <div class="card shadow-sm mb-4">
    <div class="card-body">
      <h2 class="h4">Who we need to test</h2>

      <ol class="mb-3">
        <li>Male descendants of Gov. John Endecott</li>
        <li>Male siblings and descendants of Thomas Endacott (b. 1566 in Chagford – married to Unknown)</li>
        <li>Male siblings and descendants of John Endecott (b. 1541, married Johanna Unknown)</li>
        <li>Male siblings and descendants of Henry Endecott (b. 1515, married Marjory Halse)</li>
        <li>Male Endecott spelling variations (Endicott, Endacott, Indicott, Endeacott, and many others)</li>
        <li>Males who believe they’re Endacott descendants with a different surname (due to adoption, divorce, non-parental event, etc.)</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="p-3 bg-light border rounded mb-3">
        <p class="mb-2"><strong>Financial assistance</strong> may be available case-by-case:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            Thomas Endecott’s (b. 1566 Chagford) siblings and their male descendants:
            <ul>
              <li>William Endecott (b. 1560) married Anne Ellis</li>
              <li>Robert Endecott (b. 24 Dec 1570)</li>
              <li>Richard Endecott (b. 1561)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            yDNA matches in the FTDNA database who don’t meet the above criteria but may be related to Endecotts.
            These individuals often need additional SNP testing.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <p>
        Male descendants are crucial in determining the ancestors of Gov. John Endecott.
        yDNA is passed from father to son with small mutations that accumulate over generations,
        enabling us to place each male in the correct haplogroup and subgroup.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

